---
import PageShell from '../../../../components/PageShell.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', text: 'Overview', level: 2 },
  { id: 'healthcare-system', text: 'Healthcare System', level: 2 },
  { id: 'visa-requirements', text: 'Visa Options', level: 2 },
  { id: 'insurance-requirements', text: 'Insurance Requirements', level: 2 },
  { id: 'recommended-providers', text: 'Recommended Providers', level: 2 },
  { id: 'costs', text: 'Expected Costs', level: 2 },
  { id: 'scenarios', text: 'Real-World Scenarios', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Dominican Republic Insurance Guide', href: '/countries/dominican-republic/insurance' },
  { title: 'Insurance for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors' },
  { title: 'Costa Rica for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors/in/costa-rica' },
  { title: 'Panama for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors/in/panama' },
  { title: 'Mexico for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors/in/mexico' },
];

const providerColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'entryAge', header: 'Max Entry Age' },
  { key: 'renewal', header: 'Renewal' },
  { key: 'monthlyFrom', header: 'From (65-69)' },
  { key: 'drFit', header: 'DR Fit' },
];

const providerRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', entryAge: '74', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: 'RD$18,500-26,500/mo', drFit: 'Excellent' },
  { provider: 'BUPA Global', entryAge: '79', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: 'RD$21,700-31,000/mo', drFit: 'Excellent' },
  { provider: 'GeoBlue', entryAge: '74', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: 'RD$16,700-24,000/mo', drFit: 'Very Good' },
  { provider: 'IMG Global', entryAge: '74', renewal: 'To 80', monthlyFrom: 'RD$15,000-21,500/mo', drFit: 'Good' },
  { provider: 'Dominican Local', entryAge: '65', renewal: 'Annual', monthlyFrom: 'RD$4,500-12,000/mo', drFit: 'Domestic Only' },
];

const costColumns = [
  { key: 'category', header: 'Expense' },
  { key: 'monthly', header: 'Monthly' },
  { key: 'annual', header: 'Annual' },
];

const costRows = [
  { category: 'International Insurance (65-69)', monthly: 'RD$16,700-26,500', annual: 'RD$200,400-318,000' },
  { category: 'International Insurance (70-74)', monthly: 'RD$22,800-35,000', annual: 'RD$273,600-420,000' },
  { category: 'International Insurance (75-79)', monthly: 'RD$30,800-47,200', annual: 'RD$369,600-566,400' },
  { category: 'DR Private Hospital', monthly: 'Pay per visit', annual: 'RD$1,500-4,000/visit' },
  { category: 'DR Public', monthly: 'Free/nominal', annual: 'Basic quality' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Health Insurance for Seniors in Dominican Republic 2026 | Retirement Guide"
  description="Guide to health insurance for seniors retiring in Dominican Republic. Caribbean beaches, affordable living, growing expat community, and coverage for expats 65+."
  headline="Health Insurance for Seniors in Dominican Republic"
  subheadline="Dominican Republic offers Caribbean beaches, established expat communities, improving healthcare, and affordable living—the Caribbean most accessible retirement destination."
  heroImage="/images/countries/dominican-republic-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Compare Senior Plans →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna-global"
>
  <h2 id="overview">Why Seniors Choose Dominican Republic</h2>
  <p>
    Dominican Republic offers accessible Caribbean retirement—direct flights from US and Canada, established expat communities, improving healthcare, and affordable living costs. The country is actively developing healthcare infrastructure with private hospitals expanding services.
  </p>

  <p>
    Santo Domingo has best healthcare and urban amenities. North coast (Puerto Plata, Sosua, Cabarete) has established expat communities. Punta Cana area offers resort living. Las Terrenas on Samana peninsula attracts European expats. Each region offers distinct character.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Key Facts for Seniors</h3>
    <ul class="text-primary-800 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>Healthcare:</strong> Improving; Santo Domingo best</li>
      <li><strong>Language:</strong> Spanish; English in tourist areas</li>
      <li><strong>Cost of Living:</strong> RD$55,000-140,000/month (~$1,000-2,500); affordable</li>
      <li><strong>Climate:</strong> Tropical; warm year-round</li>
      <li><strong>Character:</strong> Caribbean; music; baseball; beaches</li>
      <li><strong>Accessibility:</strong> Direct flights from many US/Canadian cities</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2 id="healthcare-system">Dominican Republic Healthcare System</h2>
  <p>
    Dominican healthcare is improving—new private hospitals expanding services. CEDIMAT, Centro Medico UCE, and Hospital Metropolitano de Santiago offer good care. Santo Domingo has best facilities. North coast has adequate private clinics. Complex cases may still require US evacuation.
  </p>

  <p>
    Private healthcare is affordable by Western standards. International insurance provides access to best facilities and evacuation if needed. Cash payment works for routine care at local clinics.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-4 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">Improving Healthcare Infrastructure</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800 mb-0">
      Dominican healthcare is improving—new private facilities, more specialists, expanding services. Santo Domingo hospitals are increasingly capable. Still recommend international insurance with US evacuation for complex cases, but local care is better than many Caribbean alternatives.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="visa-requirements">Visa Options for Seniors</h2>
  <p>
    Dominican Republic offers straightforward retirement options:
  </p>

  <h3>Pensionado (Rentista) Visa</h3>
  <p>
    For retirees with $1,500+/month guaranteed income from pension or investments. Leads to permanent residence. Reasonable threshold for Caribbean retirement. Tax benefits on foreign income.
  </p>

  <h3>Investor Residence</h3>
  <p>
    Property investment of $200,000+ qualifies for residence. Popular among expats combining property purchase with retirement.
  </p>

  <h3>Extended Stay</h3>
  <p>
    30-day tourist card extendable. Long-term stays possible through extensions, though formal residence is recommended.
  </p>

  <h2 id="insurance-requirements">Insurance Requirements</h2>
  <p>
    Insurance requirements for Dominican Republic:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Residence visa:</strong> Health insurance recommended</li>
    <li><strong>Practical need:</strong> Important for private hospital access</li>
    <li><strong>US evacuation:</strong> Valuable for complex care needs</li>
    <li><strong>Local option:</strong> Dominican insurers available but limited</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-2">Insurance Strategy for Dominican Republic</h3>
    <p class="text-blue-800 mb-0">
      International insurance with Americas coverage is recommended for Dominican Republic seniors. Local healthcare is improving but evacuation to Miami or San Juan provides backup for complex needs. Cash payment works for routine local care.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="recommended-providers">Recommended Insurance Providers</h2>
  <p>
    For seniors in Dominican Republic, Americas coverage with evacuation works well:
  </p>

  <ComparisonTable columns={providerColumns} rows={providerRows} />

  <h3>Why These Providers Work for Dominican Republic</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cigna Global:</strong> Good Americas network, Miami/San Juan access</li>
    <li><strong>BUPA Global:</strong> Highest entry age (79), comprehensive coverage</li>
    <li><strong>GeoBlue:</strong> Blue Cross network for US evacuation</li>
    <li><strong>IMG Global:</strong> Budget-friendly with Americas coverage</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-8">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Get Personalized Senior Quotes</h3>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-4">Compare coverage from providers that work well for Dominican Republic.</p>
    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3">
      <a href="/go/cigna-global" class="inline-block px-5 py-2.5 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-primary-700 transition-colors font-medium" style="color: white !important;">Get Cigna Quote</a>
      <a href="/go/bupa-global" class="inline-block px-5 py-2.5 bg-neutral-700 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-neutral-800 transition-colors font-medium" style="color: white !important;">Get BUPA Quote</a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="costs">Expected Insurance Costs</h2>
  <p>
    Insurance costs for Dominican Republic are moderate:
  </p>

  <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />

  <h3>Cost-Saving Strategies</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Higher deductibles:</strong> Dominican private care is affordable</li>
    <li><strong>Pay cash routine:</strong> Consultations RD$1,500-3,000; affordable</li>
    <li><strong>Americas-only:</strong> Skip worldwide coverage if not traveling globally</li>
    <li><strong>Puerto Rico option:</strong> Close US territory for complex care</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="scenarios">Real-World Scenarios</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Scenario 1: American Beach Lover, 67</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Situation:</strong> $2,200/month pension. North coast beach lifestyle.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Solution:</strong> Pensionado visa. Cigna Global with Miami evacuation.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0"><strong>Cost:</strong> Cigna ~RD$21,000/month (~$375). Caribbean beach; US backup healthcare.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Scenario 2: Canadian Snowbird Couple, Both 72</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Situation:</strong> Combined pension CAD 4,500/month. Sosua expat community.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Solution:</strong> BUPA Global for both. Direct flights to Toronto; local healthcare improving.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0"><strong>Cost:</strong> BUPA ~RD$52,000/month combined (~CAD 1,200). Caribbean lifestyle; established community.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Scenario 3: European Beach Seeker, 66</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Situation:</strong> €1,800/month pension. Las Terrenas, Samana.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Solution:</strong> GeoBlue with European backup. French-influenced community.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0"><strong>Cost:</strong> GeoBlue ~RD$19,000/month (~€340). European vibe; Caribbean value.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 my-8">
    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is Dominican Republic safe?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        Generally yes—tourist areas and expat communities are safe. Standard Caribbean precautions apply. North coast communities, Santo Domingo nice neighborhoods, and resort areas are secure. Petty crime exists but violent crime against expats is rare.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How affordable is the Dominican Republic?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        Very affordable—among Caribbean most affordable options. Comfortable retirement possible on $1,500-2,500/month. Local food, domestic help, and services are inexpensive. Property is reasonable. Better value than Puerto Rico, US Virgin Islands, or most Caribbean islands.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need Spanish?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        Helpful but not essential—English is common in tourist areas and expat communities. Healthcare professionals often speak English. Learning Spanish significantly improves daily life and community integration. Many expats manage with basic Spanish.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How is the expat community?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        Well-established—North coast (Sosua, Cabarete) has large American/Canadian community. Las Terrenas attracts Europeans. Santo Domingo has diverse expat population. Active social scenes, clubs, and support networks. Easy to connect with other retirees.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-8">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Ready to Compare Options?</h3>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-4">Get quotes from providers with Americas coverage for Dominican Republic.</p>
    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3">
      <a href="/go/cigna-global" class="inline-block px-5 py-2.5 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-primary-700 transition-colors font-medium" style="color: white !important;">Get Cigna Quote</a>
      <a href="/go/bupa-global" class="inline-block px-5 py-2.5 bg-neutral-700 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-neutral-800 transition-colors font-medium" style="color: white !important;">Get BUPA Quote</a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-8">
    <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600 mb-0">
      <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This guide is for informational purposes only. Insurance requirements, visa regulations, and healthcare access rules change regularly. Always verify current requirements with Dominican Republic authorities and consult with a licensed insurance professional.
    </p>
  </div>
</PageShell>
